The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, April 1: Essar Groups vice-chairman Ravi Ruia has resigned from the boards of Essar Shipping and Essar Oil to devote time to grow the groups international business. The company has received a letter dated March 31 from Ravi Ruia tendering his resignation from the board of directors of the company with immediate effect because of other commitments, Essar Shipping Ports and Logistics today said.                            
	 New Delhi, April 1: The World Steel Association has sought a probe against the global miners  Rio Tinto, BHP Billiton and Vale  by competent competition authorities for their alleged monopolistic trade practices. The demand comes after these mining firms effected a short-term iron ore supply contract with various steel producers against the previous practice of entering into annual arrangement.                            
	 New Delhi, April 1: Drug firm AstraZeneca Pharma and Bristol-Myers Squibb India have entered into an alliance to develop and market two anti-diabetic drugs in the country.                             
	 New Delhi, April 1: The government has allowed bulk sugar users like soft drink and ice cream manufacturers to import raw sugar at zero duty from today to keep the prices of the sweetener at a reasonable level.                            
	 New Delhi, April 1: Indias fiscal deficit shot up over 23 per cent to Rs 3.80 lakh crore in the first eleven months of this fiscal mainly on the overruns because of the stimulus measures taken by the government during the slowdown last year.                            
	 New Delhi, April 1: Inox Wind Limited has successfully commissioned the commercial production of its wind turbine generator manufacturing unit in Himachal Pradesh.                            
	 Mumbai, April 1: The Bombay Stock Exchange, NSE, forex and money market will remain closed tomorrow on account of Good Friday.                                                                                                                          
